# ============================================================
#  MINDSTATZ — Environment Variables & Deployment Checklist
# ============================================================
#
#  GitHub Pages is static — these values go directly into
#  index.html and admin.html as window.SUPABASE_* variables.
#  Do NOT commit real keys to a public repo.
#  Use a private repo, or move keys to a build step / worker.
# ============================================================

# ── Supabase (find these at: supabase.com → Project → Settings → API) ──
SUPABASE_URL=https://YOUR_PROJECT_REF.supabase.co
SUPABASE_ANON_KEY=YOUR_ANON_PUBLIC_KEY          # safe to expose client-side

# ── Edge Function Secrets (set via Supabase CLI — never in the browser) ──
# Generate a 32-byte hex key:
#   node -e "console.log(require('crypto').randomBytes(32).toString('hex'))"
MINDSTATZ_AES_KEY=YOUR_64_CHAR_HEX_KEY

# The service role key is set automatically in Edge Functions
# SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY=...  ← managed by Supabase, don't set manually


# ============================================================
#  DEPLOYMENT CHECKLIST — run in order
# ============================================================

# ── Step 1: Supabase Project Setup ───────────────────────────
# 1. Go to https://supabase.com → New Project
# 2. Note your Project URL and anon public key
# 3. Go to SQL Editor → New Query
# 4. Paste and run the contents of supabase-setup.sql
# 5. Verify tables created: profiles, videos, access_tokens,
#    session_log, site_config

# ── Step 2: Configure Credentials in HTML ────────────────────
# In BOTH index.html and admin.html, find this block and fill in:
#
#   window.SUPABASE_URL  = 'https://YOUR_PROJECT_REF.supabase.co';
#   window.SUPABASE_ANON = 'YOUR_ANON_PUBLIC_KEY';

# ── Step 3: Deploy Edge Function ─────────────────────────────
# Install Supabase CLI:   npm install -g supabase
# Login:                  supabase login
# Link project:           supabase link --project-ref YOUR_PROJECT_REF
#
# Set the AES secret (generate key first — see above):
#   supabase secrets set MINDSTATZ_AES_KEY=your_64_char_hex
#
# Deploy the function:
#   supabase functions deploy get-video-url
#
# Test it:
#   supabase functions serve get-video-url --env-file .env

# ── Step 4: Create Your Admin Account ────────────────────────
# 1. Push your site to GitHub Pages
# 2. Open your site → click Sign In → create an account
#    with your admin email
# 3. In Supabase Dashboard → Table Editor → profiles
# 4. Find your row → set role = 'admin'
#    OR run in SQL Editor:
#      UPDATE profiles SET role = 'admin'
#      WHERE email = 'your@email.com';
# 5. Sign in to the site → you'll be redirected to admin.html

# ── Step 5: Upload Your First Video ──────────────────────────
# 1. Go to admin.html → Upload Videos
# 2. Enter title, video URL (CDN link or assets/ path), type, access
# 3. Click "Encrypt & Save Video"
#    → AES-256-GCM encrypts the URL + metadata in your browser
#    → Only the ciphertext is stored in Supabase
#    → Members get URLs via the Edge Function after JWT verification

# ── Step 6: Enable Email Confirmations (optional) ────────────
# Supabase Dashboard → Authentication → Email Templates
# Customize the confirmation email with your branding

# ── Step 7: Set Up CORS on Your CDN ──────────────────────────
# If hosting videos on Cloudinary / Bunny.net / S3:
# Add your GitHub Pages domain to the CDN's allowed origins:
#   https://yourusername.github.io

# ── Security Notes ───────────────────────────────────────────
# • The ANON key is safe to expose — it only allows what RLS permits
# • The SERVICE ROLE key must NEVER go in the browser
# • The AES key lives only in Supabase Secrets + admin's memory (PBKDF2)
# • Admin passwords are SHA-256 hashed (with UUID salt) in the DB
# • Video URLs are AES-256-GCM encrypted — DB admins cannot read them
# • All IPs in the audit log are stored as SHA-256 hashes (never raw)
# • Session JWTs are short-lived (1 hour) — Supabase handles refresh
